<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="22" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="22">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="22">The most particular character to diagnose this genus is the shape of the head, which is anteriorly prolonged, strongly tapering and triangular. Other diagnostic characters are: elongate body, shiny and glabrous; eyes moderately salient; pronotal base lobate; scutellum long and,triangular.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="22" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="22">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="22">
Two species from Brazil, one of these with a subspecies in Northeastern Argentina which was separated from the typical form by 
<bibRefCitation author="Monros, F" journalOrPublisher="Acta Zoologica Lilloana" pageId="61" pageNumber="72" pagination="5 - 274" title="Revision sistematica de las especies de Clytrinae de la Argentina, Paraguay, Uruguay y Chile (Col. Chrysomelidae)." volume="14" year="1953 a">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Monrós">Monros</normalizedToken>
(1953a)
</bibRefCitation>
on the basis of its smaller size and distinct punctuation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
